Cell["\<\
The normalization term is somewhat complex, and it is likely that a much \
cheaper function could be fitted to it. In addition, the normalization factor \
causes this function to have (removable) singularities at \[Alpha]abc2 = 1.0 \
and \[Alpha]abc2 = 2.0 (another reason to fit a simpler function, which would \
presumably not have these removable singularities).

In the following graphs we will avoid these exact values by adding a small \
epsilon where needed. Since the parameter space is two-dimensional, we\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll need more plots:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.552872254527713*^9, 3.552872301528717*^9}, {
   3.552878103271337*^9, 3.552878196779132*^9}, {3.5529581247968397`*^9, 
   3.552958168031698*^9}, {3.552963542229061*^9, 3.552963569676888*^9}, {
   3.552964853811884*^9, 3.55296487421532*^9}, {3.555043048707852*^9, 
   3.55504306437694*^9}, 3.555045264017606*^9, {3.555092751893256*^9, 
   3.555092803984524*^9}, {3.556150885108983*^9, 3.556150886266168*^9}}],

